{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522475"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13832"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13832"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.79,0.16,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101840"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6449"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84296"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3475"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39820"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43919"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101840"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing and painless abdominal distension. He has no other symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks four glasses of wine daily. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Views of his abdomen are shown (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of these clinical findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior vena cava obstruction","Portal hypertension","Inferior vena cava obstruction","Pelvic vein insufficiency","Superior mesenteric vein thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe images show a distended abdomen with dilated subcutaneous veins radiating from the umbilicus, known as caput medusae. This finding, combined with the history of chronic alcohol consumption and progressive abdominal distension, is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eportal hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E. Portal hypertension occurs when there is increased resistance to blood flow through the portal venous system, most commonly due to cirrhosis. The increased pressure causes blood to seek alternative routes through collateral vessels, including the paraumbilical veins, which become dilated and visible on the abdominal wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior vena cava obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with facial and neck swelling, distended neck veins, and upper extremity edema. The collateral venous pattern would be more prominent in the upper chest and neck region rather than the abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior vena cava obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E would cause bilateral lower extremity edema and potentially dilated superficial veins on the lower abdomen and legs, but the pattern would not typically radiate from the umbilicus as seen in caput medusae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic vein insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the pelvis and lower extremities with varicose veins and would not cause the radiating pattern of dilated veins from the umbilicus seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior mesenteric vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute abdominal pain and often intestinal ischemia. While it can contribute to portal hypertension if chronic, it would not be the primary diagnosis given this patient\u0027s presentation with painless, progressive abdominal distension and chronic alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s history of significant alcohol consumption (four glasses of wine daily) is a major risk factor for developing cirrhosis, which is the most common cause of portal hypertension. The abdominal distension is likely due to ascites, another common manifestation of portal hypertension. Additional findings that might be present but are not visible in the images include splenomegaly, jaundice, and other signs of chronic liver disease such as palmar erythema and spider naevi.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dilated abdominal wall veins (caput medusae) radiating from the umbilicus are a classic sign of portal hypertension.","Chronic alcohol consumption is a major risk factor for developing cirrhosis and subsequent portal hypertension.","Portal hypertension leads to the development of portosystemic collaterals as blood seeks alternative routes around the obstructed portal vein."],"references":["Iwakiri Y. Pathophysiology of Portal Hypertension. Clin Liver Dis. 2014; 18: 281\u201391. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24679494/","Stanford Univeristy. 2025. Ascited and venous patterns. Available at: https://stanfordmedicine25.stanford.edu/the25/avp.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84296"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13832"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20779"},{"type":"media","id":"21550"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20779"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nRmTNk9IgeI5s4szwKtnAZe8ARA8ca.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nRmTNk9IgeI5s4szwKtnAZe8ARA8ca.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"media","id":"21550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21550"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Gjr4lZffUr4SZOS4tsiZXbaHQDl09p.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Gjr4lZffUr4SZOS4tsiZXbaHQDl09p.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84296"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-04T16:15:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-04T16:16:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6449"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101840"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":